('129115403803409_1235398826474530', 'The traffic sergeant in the picture, at Behala Chowrasta James Long Sarani Crossing, has been illegally harassing all the motorists, cab drivers & bus drivers for the last few days, in the cover of checking the vehicle papers. My driver was also the victim of him yesterday. He was asking for the commercial permit of a vehicle which has been bought just ten days back. The permit is only available after 3 months of a vehicle purchase. He was shown the TR7 challan, but was not satisfied. He only let him go after a unofficial fine of 200/-.', '2016-01-12T10:12:26+0000', 'negative'),
('129115403803409_1238896742845862', 'Request: Please Do Not Breed Ashrafs in your system.\n\nHi, I am a working professional and a mother who drives down every day to pick my child from school. But today, the 27th of January 2017 was very different.\nI was waiting to take an U-Turn from the Corporation Garage stoppage (before Entally crossing) at around 10am. The traffic signal went green for me to take the turn and red for vehicles coming from Entally. I was taking the turn and just then, a public bus, violated the signal and screeched to halt at only an inch away from my car. \nI was totally shocked and looked at the uniformed traffic police guy standing there at the junction. Contrary to what I expected, he waved at the bus driver throwing a smile and gestured him to move on. He did not even note down the bus number. \nShocked by his reaction to the incident, I decided to walk up to this man in blue uniform and find out what stopped him from taking the bus driver to task. I asked him his name. He denied identity, but I later came to know from others that his name is Ashraf. My conversation with Ashraf follows:\n• Myself: Apni ekhane ki korte achen? (Why are you here?)\n• Ashraf: Ami ekhaner traffic police. (I am the traffic police here.)\n• Myself: Ki hoto jodi bus ta mere deeto amay? (What would have happened if I were hit?\n• Ashraf: Dile dito. Ami ki korbo. (if it were to happen, it would have happened, what can I do). \n• Myself: Merey dito toh amar baccha taar ki hoto? (what would have happened to my kid, if I was hit?) \n• Ashraf: Barite aaro onek lok aache nischoi dakhaar (There are people at home, I am sure, to look after your kid).\nSo, according to Ashraf, this man in uniform, it is okay to be hit if I have others to look after my kid at home. \nMy humble question to your department: If there were not anyone to look after someone\'s kid after he or she is hit, would it be written all over that person for traffic guys like Ashraf to take a traffic control decision? Is it not their duty first to make every vehicle compliant to traffic rules and penalize the ones that don\'t? In what capacity does a traffic police be lenient to \'specific\' vehicles and disrespectful to ordinary citizens who approach him?\nAlthough later I spoke to the sergeant on duty there and he assured action against Ashraf, I feel compelled to bring this matter to broader notice. I would like to see tangible action being taken against these kinds of men in uniform who are audacious, unlawful and arrogant. As an ordinary citizen, I do not know how these men are recruited into the traffic department, but I can at least appeal to you that teach them manners, if you can\'t teach them their duty.\nI would like to regain my faith in the Kolkata Traffic Police, and look forward to justice very soon. Best regards!', '2017-01-27T13:28:11+0000', 'positive'),
