('129115403803409_1434299249951678', 'WB04F 7989. This is the number of 217B bus I took from Dharmatala to reach VIP Joramandir at around 10.10-10.15pm. I am in the editorial team of a daily newspaper and I have to travel back by bus because of my shift. During Phool bagan to Hudco, the speed was so dangerous that no one could even sit without bumping his head. It almost collided with another bus and when we protested, the conductor proudly said, \'<U+09B9><U+09DF> <U+098F><U+0987> <U+09B8><U+09CD><U+09AA><U+09BF><U+09A1><U+09C7> <U+09AC><U+09BE><U+09B8> <U+09AF><U+09BE><U+09AC><U+09C7>, <U+09A8><U+09DF><U+09A4><U+09CB> <U+09AF><U+09BE><U+09AC><U+09C7> <U+09A8><U+09BE>\' (either it will maintain that speed or won\'t move at all). Every 271B and 30C/1 from Dharmatala after 10pm does this and we, common people, returning from our office close our eyes and pray: please keep me safe tonight. The suffering continues with people having \'biri\' at the door and leave the smoke on the face of the lady sitting behind, misbehaving conductors, eve-teasers and many more. I am a 27 years old girl working in media. I can only shout on their face and if fortunate, get the support of few others. But this speed limit thing is scaring me off. I know it\'s not possible to watch every bus in this city or the situation inside it. But if your department take step for just one time in these late night incidents, we can atleast talk back to the conductors and scare them instead for a few days. There are thousands of independent girls like me in the city who want to get back home safely. Our parents want us to come home. Today that bus made me feel near-death experience, and I had enough. Will be really thankful if something can be done. Thank you.', '2017-11-21T17:35:38+0000', 'neutral'),
