('129115403803409_1569554283092840', 'I have received a number of notices for violation of traffic lights over the past couple of months. Few I have paid fines to the police officer booking me for violation, few must have registered in the server for which I will have to pay fines eventually. As a law abiding regular citizen, I do not mind paying such fines but I have a feeling that over a past couple of months this fining for violations has gone into a revenue collection spree, where law enforcers are passing on all judgments to close circuit camera without considering the circumstances and conditions under which such bookings are made by your system.\n\nSir, my driving licence is roughly 18 years old so you can be reasonably assured that I am just not a tourist driving around in metropolitan city of Kolkata. May I draw your kind attention to busy traffic crossings of Kolkata, like say Gariahat or Rasbehari? Does traffic light mean much at such junctions where down lane vehicles continue to take turns directly across up lane cars under green signals? Does traffic light mean much when there is absolutely no pedestrian separation at such crossings where people jaywalk before the cars with impunity? Does it not seem that all violation laws are directed at vehicle owners?\n\nMy everyday experience is that the traffic light signalling in Kolkata is a sham, sir. On many ocassions, the lights turn red from green with a milisecond yellow in between and catch cars right at the crossing as offenders. In many places, traffic lights are not visible from behind tall buses, or are obscured by trees, and your officers continue to book and fine people who have no way to defend themselves. I am sure you know on many ocassions traffic constables give hand signals contradictory to light signals (signal showing red but police indicating to move). How fair and neutral do you think the system, sir? Is it fair to book a car driver just for the sake of a rule without judging his/her intent? Is that the way how a public servant discharges his duty?\n\nAs a citizen I welcome hiking the fines for traffic offences. But the other side of the coin should be strictly administeted streets with properly placed traffic lights and signals, clear and visible road marks, no parking or claming zone signs, pedestrian segregation from streets, and most importantly disallowing pandals, vending shops and other syructures encroaching the streets. If these are not done, it may appear that the traffic police are entrapping car owners and drivers in the maze of city roads and filling coffers of the state unjustly.\n\nThis said, I also do appreciate the risk, stress and toughness of the working conditions of traffic police in Kolkata.', '2018-04-20T08:21:47+0000', 'neutral'),
